What is GCS : 
=============
"GCS is a globally scalable object storage service offering multiple storage classes, flexible location options, IAM-based access control, lifecycle management, and strong security integrations. 
 Itâ€™s ideal for unstructured data, backups, analytics, and ML workloads."
 Used for static content, backups, analytics, ML

1.0 Core Building Blocks of GCS :
=================================
  1.1 Bucket :
  ------------
  A bucket is the top-level container.
  Important properties:
  Bucket name is globally unique 
  Bucket has a location
  Bucket has a storage class
  Bucket has IAM policies
  Bucket can have lifecycle rules
ðŸ“Œ Interview tip:
  We cannot change bucket location after creation.

  1.2 Object :
  -------------
  An object is the actual data (file)
  Each object has:
    Name
    Data
    Metadata
    Generation number (for versioning)
ðŸ“Œ Objects are immutable â†’ update = upload new version.

 2.0 Bucket Location Options (Very Important ðŸ”¥)
 ================================================
   2.1 Region
   -----------
    Example: asia-south1, us-central1
    Use when:
      Low latency needed
      Data residency laws
      Applications running in same region
  ðŸ“Œ Interview example:
       If my users are in India and app is in asia-south1, Iâ€™ll choose regional bucket.
   2.2 Dual-Region :
   -----------------
   Example:
     asia1 (Mumbai + Singapore)
     eur4 (Netherlands + Finland)
   Use when:
     High availability
     Disaster recovery
   Read-heavy workloads
  ðŸ“Œ Data automatically replicated across two regions.
  ðŸ“Œ Interview one-liner:
        Dual-region provides higher availability without managing replication manually.
  2.3 Multi-Region :
  ------------------
  Example:
    US
    EU
    ASIA
  Use when:
    Global users
    CDN-style workloads
    Static websites
 ðŸ“Œ Highest availability, slightly higher cost.

 3.0 : Storage Classes (MOST ASKED) : 
 ====================================
   3.1 Standard Storage
   ---------------------
       Hot data
         Used for: 
           Frequently accessed data
           Websites
           Mobile apps
           Streaming
         Characteristics:
           High availability
           No minimum storage duration
      ðŸ“Œ Interview line:
           Standard is best when data is accessed frequently.
   
   3.2 Nearline Storage :
   ---------------------
      Accessed once a month
        Used for:
          Monthly backups
          DR snapshots
        Rules:
          Minimum 30-day storage
          Retrieval cost exists
     ðŸ“Œ Interview comparison:
          Nearline is cheaper than Standard but has access cost.

    3.3 Coldline Storage :
    ----------------------
      Accessed once per quarter
        Used for:
          Compliance backups
          Long-term logs
        Rules:
          Minimum 90-day storage
          Higher access cost

    3.4 : Archive Storage :
    -----------------------
      Very rarely accessed (once a year)
        Used for:
          Legal data
          Audit records
          Long-term retention
        Rules:
          Minimum 365-day storage
          Cheapest storage
          Highest retrieval cost
     ðŸ“Œ Interview trick question:
           Archive is not â€œslow like tapeâ€ â€” itâ€™s still online, just expensive to read.

  4.0 Access Control Options (IAM vs ACL) :
  =========================================
    4.1 IAM (Recommended âœ…)
    -------------------------
       Controls who can do what on bucket or objects
       Roles:
         storage.objectViewer
         storage.objectAdmin
         storage.admin
     ðŸ“Œ Best practice:
           Use IAM, not ACL.

     4.2 Uniform vs Fine-grained Access :
     ------------------------------------
       > Uniform Bucket-Level Access (Recommended)
           Disable ACLs
           IAM only
           Simpler and secure
       > Fine-grained
           Allows ACL + IAM
           Complex
           Legacy setups
      ðŸ“Œ Interview best answer:
            Always use uniform access unless legacy systems require ACLs.

  5.0 Object Versioning :
  =======================
    5.1 What it does :
    -------------------
       Keeps old versions of objects
       Prevents accidental deletes or overwrites
     Use cases:
       Rollback
       Audit
       Safety net
    ðŸ“Œ Important:
          Deleted objects become non-current versions, not removed.

  6.0 Lifecycle Management Rules (Cost Optimization ðŸ”¥)
  ======================================================
     Automatically move or delete objects.
     Examples:
       After 30 days â†’ move to Nearline
       After 365 days â†’ Archive
      Delete old versions after 90 days
  ðŸ“Œ Interview scenario:
        Lifecycle rules help reduce storage cost automatically.

  7.0 Retention Policies & Legal Hold (Compliance) :
  ==================================================
   7.1 Retention Policy
   --------------------
      Prevent deletion for X days/years
      Cannot be bypassed
   7.2 Legal Hold :
   ----------------
      Locks individual objects
      Used for investigations
  ðŸ“Œ Interview usage:
        Used in finance, healthcare, compliance workloads.

 8.0 Encryption Options :
 ========================
  8.1 Google-managed keys (Default)
  ---------------------------------
    Automatic
    No management
  8.2 Customer-managed keys (CMEK)
  --------------------------------
    Stored in Cloud KMS
    You control rotation & access
  8.3 Customer-supplied keys (CSEK)
  ---------------------------------
    You provide key per request
    Least used, complex
ðŸ“Œ Interview pick:
      CMEK is best for compliance-driven environments.

 9.0 Data Access Options :
 ========================
  9.1 Signed URLs
  ---------------
    Time-limited access
    No IAM needed
  9.2 Signed Policy Documents
  ---------------------------
    Browser-based uploads
 ðŸ“Œ Interview use case:
       Allow temporary access to private objects.

 10.0 Networking Options :
 =========================
   10.1 Public Access
   ------------------
      Objects accessible via URL
   10.2 Private Access 
   --------------------
      IAM controlled
   10.3 VPC Service Controls 
   -------------------------
     Protect against data exfiltration
  ðŸ“Œ Interview line:
        VPC Service Controls add an extra security boundary.

 11.0 Pricing Factors (Interview Must-Know) :
 ============================================
   Pricing depends on:
  --------------------
     Storage class
     Location
     Data access
     Network egress
     Operations (GET, PUT)
ðŸ“Œ Golden rule:
     Storage is cheap, access is what costs.

